      <h2>Safety</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Read all safety warnings, instructions, illustrations and specifications provided with this power tool,
        including the battery and charger sections. Failure to follow them may result in electric shock, fire,
        and/or serious injury. Save all warnings and instructions for future reference.
      </div>

      <h3>Personal protection</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Always wear ANSI Z87.1 safety glasses</strong> (CAN/CSA Z94.3). Everyday eyeglasses are not safety glasses. Add a face or dust mask when the work is dusty.</li>
        <li><strong>Wear ANSI S12.6 (S3.19) hearing protection</strong> &mdash; noise from this tool can contribute to hearing loss.</li>
        <li>Use NIOSH/OSHA/MSHA-approved respiratory protection. Sanding, sawing and grinding can generate dust containing chemicals (lead, crystalline silica, arsenic/chromium) known to cause cancer or reproductive harm.</li>
        <li>Prolonged vibration can permanently injure fingers, hands and arms. Wear gloves for extra cushion, take frequent breaks, and limit daily use.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Operating safety</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Hold the tool by the insulated gripping surfaces</strong> when the accessory may contact hidden wiring. A live wire will energize exposed metal parts and shock the operator. Check for hidden wiring, gas lines and utilities before cutting or removing material.</li>
        <li><strong>Clamp or secure the workpiece</strong> to a stable platform. Holding work by hand or against your body is unstable and can cause loss of control.</li>
        <li><strong>Wait for the accessory to stop</strong> before setting the tool down &mdash; an exposed, moving accessory can grab the surface.</li>
        <li>Do not restart a cut inside the workpiece. Let the tool reach full speed, then carefully re-enter the cut.</li>
        <li>Do not jam the blade, apply excessive pressure, or attempt an excessive depth of cut.</li>
        <li>Keep hands away from the cutting area; never reach under the material being cut.</li>
        <li>Use only sharp, undamaged accessories. Bent blades break or kick back. Accessories are sharp and become hot &mdash; wear gloves to change them and let them cool first.</li>
        <li>Before scraping, check the workpiece for nails &mdash; remove them or set them below the finished surface.</li>
        <li>Dry use only. Do not wet sand, and never work in areas soaked or dampened with liquid &mdash; liquid entering the motor housing is a shock hazard, and scraping action can heat liquids into harmful vapors.</li>
        <li>Avoid air vents, which often cover moving parts. Keep loose clothing, jewelry and long hair clear.</li>
        <li>Remove the battery pack before making adjustments or changing accessories &mdash; an accidental start-up can cause injury.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="warning">
        Risk of lacerations or burns. Never touch the sharp edges of accessories. Do not touch the workpiece or
        blade immediately after operating &mdash; they can become very hot. Allow accessories and the workpiece to
        cool before handling.
      </div>

      <div class="danger">
        Fire hazard when sanding metal: do not use a vacuum (sparks are generated). Never sand magnesium surfaces.
        Do not wet sand.
      </div>

      <h3>Sanding lead-based paint</h3>
      <div class="note">
        Sanding lead-based paint is <strong>not recommended</strong> &mdash; the contaminated dust is difficult to
        control and is most dangerous to children and pregnant women. If paint must be sanded, seal the area with
        4-mil plastic sheeting, wear a NIOSH-approved lead-rated respirator, keep children and pregnant women out of
        the work area, do not eat/drink/smoke in the area, and vacuum and clean all surfaces daily. Dispose of dust,
        chips and drop cloths in sealed receptacles.
      </div>

      <h2>Battery</h2>

      <h3>Installing and Removing the Battery Pack (Fig. I)</h3>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcs356/figI.jpg" alt="Fig. I showing a 20V Max battery pack aligned with the rails in the base of the tool handle, with callout 9 for the release button and callout 8 for the battery pack" />
        <figcaption>Fig. I &mdash; align the battery pack with the rails in the handle and slide it in until firmly seated</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>To install: align the battery pack <strong>(8)</strong> with the rails inside the tool handle and slide it in until it is firmly seated and will not disengage.</li>
        <li>To remove: press the release button <strong>(9)</strong> and firmly pull the battery pack out of the handle.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">For best results, make sure the battery pack is fully charged before use.</div>

      <h2>Installing &amp; Removing Accessories</h2>

      <h3>Tool-Free Quick-Change System (Fig. B, C)</h3>
      <p>
        The tool features an exclusive tool-free system for faster accessory changes &mdash; no wrenches or hex keys
        required.
      </p>

      <div class="image-row">
        <div class="figure">
          <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcs356/figB.jpg" alt="Fig. B detail of the accessory clamp lever (3) opened, the tool shaft (12), and an accessory engaging the alignment pins (13) on the holder" />
          <figcaption>Fig. B &mdash; clamp lever (3), shaft (12), and accessory pins (13)</figcaption>
        </div>
        <div class="figure">
          <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcs356/figC.jpg" alt="Fig. C showing an accessory such as a scraper blade mounted on the tool shaft at an angle" />
          <figcaption>Fig. C &mdash; accessories can be mounted at an angle</figcaption>
        </div>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Grasp the tool and squeeze the accessory clamping lever <strong>(3)</strong>.</li>
        <li>Clean any residual debris from the tool shaft <strong>(12)</strong> and the clamping lever.</li>
        <li>Slide the accessory between the shaft and the lever, making sure it engages all the pins <strong>(13)</strong> on the holder and sits flush with the shaft.</li>
        <li>Release the clamping lever.</li>
        <li>Scrapers and blades can be mounted at an angle if required (Fig. C).</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Attaching Accessories with the Universal Adapter (Fig. E)</h3>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcs356/figE.jpg" alt="Fig. E exploded view showing a non-DeWalt accessory stacked between a washer (14) and the adapter nut (15) on the universal adapter" />
        <figcaption>Fig. E &mdash; universal adapter for non-DeWalt accessories</figcaption>
      </div>

      <p>Non-DeWalt accessories can be attached using the universal adapter:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Place the washer <strong>(14)</strong> on the tool.</li>
        <li>Place the accessory onto the washer.</li>
        <li>Tighten and secure the adapter nut <strong>(15)</strong> using the hex wrench.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="warning">
        Ensure the adapter and accessory are securely tightened, and do not use any accessory in an application where
        the adapter may fail to hold it. Read and follow all manufacturers' safety warnings for any accessory used.
      </div>

      <h3>Installing / Removing Sanding Sheets (Fig. D)</h3>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcs356/figD.jpg" alt="Fig. D diamond-shaped hook-and-loop sanding platen with arrows showing a triangular sanding sheet being pressed onto the platen" />
        <figcaption>Fig. D &mdash; diamond sanding platen with hook-and-loop sheet</figcaption>
      </div>

      <p>The diamond-shaped platen uses a hook-and-loop system, so it works on large flat surfaces and in tight corners.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Attach the sanding platen as described under the Quick-Change system above.</li>
        <li>Align the edges of the sheet with the edges of the platen and press it on.</li>
        <li>Press the base firmly against a flat surface and briefly switch the tool on &mdash; this seats the sheet and prevents premature wear.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="note">When the tip of the sheet wears, detach it from the platen, rotate it, and reapply.</div>

      <h2>Cut &amp; Depth Guides (Optional Accessories)</h2>

      <h3>Attaching the Cut Guide (Fig. F)</h3>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcs356/figF.jpg" alt="Fig. F exploded view of the cut guide block attaching to the accessory side mount (5) with tabs (16), secured by the screw (17), washer (14), and hex wrench (18)" />
        <figcaption>Fig. F &mdash; mounting the cut guide block to the side mount</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Insert the tabs <strong>(16)</strong> on the cut guide block <strong>(6)</strong> into the accessory side mount <strong>(5)</strong> on the main body.</li>
        <li>Secure the block with the supplied screw <strong>(17)</strong> and washer <strong>(14)</strong>, tightening with the supplied hex wrench <strong>(18)</strong>.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Depth Guide (Fig. G)</h3>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcs356/figG.jpg" alt="Fig. G the cut guide block mounted on the tool with the guide arm (7) inserted in the front slot and the depth/cut adjustment knob (19) for setting cut depth" />
        <figcaption>Fig. G &mdash; depth guide set up for a precise cut depth</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Insert the guide arm <strong>(7)</strong> into the front slot on the guide block <strong>(6)</strong>.</li>
        <li>Pull out or push in the arm to set the desired cut depth.</li>
        <li>Turn the depth/cut adjustment knob <strong>(19)</strong> clockwise to lock; counterclockwise to release.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Cut Guide (Fig. H)</h3>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcs356/figH.jpg" alt="Fig. H the cut guide arm (7) inserted into the side slots of the cut guide block (6), secured by the depth/cut adjustment knob (19), for tracking a marked cut line" />
        <figcaption>Fig. H &mdash; cut guide arm fitted to track a marked line</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Insert the guide arm <strong>(7)</strong> into the slots on the left and right sides of the cut guide block <strong>(6)</strong>.</li>
        <li>Pull out or push in the arm to set the desired length.</li>
        <li>Turn the depth/cut adjustment knob <strong>(19)</strong> clockwise to lock; counterclockwise to release.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="note">The guide arm can also be set vertically in the guard assembly to set the height of a cut.</div>

      <h2>Operation</h2>

      <h3>Variable Speed Trigger (Fig. A, J)</h3>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcs356/figJ.jpg" alt="Fig. J showing the proper one-handed grip on the main handle (11) with an accessory attached to the head of the oscillating tool" />
        <figcaption>Fig. J &mdash; proper hand position, one hand on the main handle (11)</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Make sure the switch is OFF, then install the battery pack.</li>
        <li>To turn the tool ON, hold it as shown in Fig. J and press the variable speed trigger <strong>(1)</strong>. The further the trigger is depressed, the faster it oscillates.</li>
        <li>To turn the tool OFF, release the trigger.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="warning">
        To reduce the risk of serious injury, always keep one hand on the main handle <strong>(11)</strong> and hold
        the tool securely in anticipation of a sudden reaction.
      </div>

      <h3>Mode Selector &mdash; 3 Speeds (DCS356)</h3>
      <p>
        The mode selector <strong>(10)</strong> sets one of three speed modes. Choose the mode for the application,
        then fine-tune within that range using the variable speed trigger.
      </p>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Mode</th><th>No-load speed</th><th>Typical use</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Speed 1</td><td>0&ndash;13,000&nbsp;OPM</td><td>Controlled detail work, delicate materials</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Speed 2</td><td>0&ndash;17,000&nbsp;OPM</td><td>General-purpose cutting and sanding</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Speed 3</td><td>0&ndash;20,000&nbsp;OPM</td><td>Fastest material removal and cutting</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>Lock On/Off Button (Fig. A)</h3>
      <p>The lock button <strong>(4)</strong> has three positions:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Trigger released, button pushed fully left or right</strong> until it snaps &mdash; locks the trigger OFF so it cannot be depressed.</li>
        <li><strong>Button centered</strong> &mdash; trigger operates normally.</li>
        <li><strong>Trigger depressed, then button pushed left or right</strong> &mdash; locks the trigger ON for comfort during extended use. Press the trigger again to release the lock; the tool stops when the trigger is released.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="note">With the lock-on engaged, the tool automatically shuts off after 5 minutes. To restart, release the trigger and re-press the lock-on button.</div>

      <h3>LED Worklight (Fig. A)</h3>
      <p>
        The LED worklight <strong>(2)</strong> turns on whenever the trigger is depressed and stays on for
        20 seconds after the trigger is released. It lights the immediate work surface and is not a flashlight.
      </p>
      <div class="warning">Do not stare into the worklight &mdash; serious eye injury could result.</div>

      <h3>Helpful hints</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Always clamp the workpiece firmly &mdash; any movement affects cut or sanding quality.</li>
        <li>Don't sand without the sandpaper attached to the platen. Use coarse grit for rough surfaces, medium for smooth, and fine for finishing; test on scrap first if unsure.</li>
        <li>Let the tool do the work with light pressure and long sweeping strokes. Excessive force reduces efficiency and overloads the motor.</li>
        <li>Don't rest your fingers on the platen during use. Don't let sandpaper wear through &mdash; it will damage the pad.</li>
        <li>Keep blades sharp and replace accessories regularly for best efficiency.</li>
      </ul>

